definition.value: An organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of 5-acetamido-4-hydroxy-3-(phenyldiazenyl)naphthalene-2,7-disulfonic acid.

A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is 3-(phenyldiazenyl)naphthalene-2,7-disulfonic acid carrying additional phenyldiazenyl, hydroxy and acetamido substituents at position 3, 4, and 5 respectively. The disodium salt is the biological stain 'azophloxine'.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo groups of 5-acetamido-4-hydroxy-3-(phenyldiazenyl)naphthalene-2,7-disulfonic acid.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of prenyl-FMNH2; major species at pH 7.3.

An organic sodium salt that is the trisodium salt of 4-hydroxy-7-[({5-hydroxy-6-[(3-methoxyphenyl)diazenyl]-7-sulfonaphthalen-2-yl}carbamoyl)amino]-3-[(6-sulfonaphthalen-2-yl)diazenyl]naphthalene-2-sulfonic acid. A direct cotton dye that is also capable of hydrogen bonding to amyloid and giving a dark enough red colour to be useful in diagnostic histology.

A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is the free acid form of the dye benzo scarlet 4BNS. The trisodium salt is a direct cotton dye that is also capable of hydrogen bonding to amyloid and giving a dark enough red colour to be useful in diagnostic histology.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo groups of benzo scarlet 4BNS free acid.
A dye that is a mixture of methyl blue and water blue. Used for staining collagen in Masson's trichrome and Mallory's method for connective tissue.

An organic sodium salt that is the trisodium salt of 4,4'-{({4-[(4-sulfophenyl)imino]cyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-ylidene}methylene)bis[(4,1-phenylene)azanediyl]}di(benzene-1-sulfonic acid). A histological dye that can be used either on its own or part of a mixture (aniline blue WS) for staining collagen in Masson's trichrome and Mallory's method for connective tissue.

An amino oligosaccharide that is a dodecasaccharide derivative in which two alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl tetrasaccharide chains are linked (1->3) and (1->6) to the mannose residue of a beta-D-mannosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->6)]-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine branched tetrasaccharide.
A fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of (R)-2-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (R)-2-hydroxybutanoic acid
An oxysterol that is cholesterol which is substituted by an oxo group at position 3 and hydroxy groups at positions 7alpha and 26. It has R-configuration at position 25.
An arenesulfonic acid, the disodium salt of which is the histological dye 'methyl blue' (used for staining collagen in Masson's trichrome and Mallory's method for connective tissue).
A mixture comprising four closely related phenazine derivatives mauveine A, mauveine B, mauveine B2 and  mauveine C. A violet coloured dye.

An organic cation consisting of 7-(4-methylanilino)phenazine carrying additional methyl, amino and phenyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 5 respectively. One of four components of mauvaine, a syntheteic violet-coloured dye.

An organic cation consisting of 1,8-dimethyl-3-(4-methylanilino)phenazine carrying additional phenyl and amino substituents at positions 5 and 7 respectively. One of four components of mauvaine, a syntheteic violet-coloured dye.

An organic cation consisting of 7-(4-methylanilino)phenazine carrying additional methyl, amino and 4-methylphenyl substituents at positions 2, 3 and 5 respectively. One of four components of mauvaine, a syntheteic violet-coloured dye.

An organic cation consisting of 1,8-dimethyl-3-(4-methylanilino)phenazine carrying additional 4-methylphenyl and amino substituents at positions 5 and 7 respectively. One of four components of mauvaine, a syntheteic violet-coloured dye.
An organosulfonate salt composed from 2-methoxy-4-nitrobenzene-1-diazonium and 5-sulfonaphthalene-1-sulfonate in a 1:1 ratio. Used for demostrating enterochromaffin in carcinoid tumours.
The aromatic diazonium ion formed from diazotisation of 2-methoxy-4-nitroaniline. The 5-sulfonaphthalene-1-sulfonate salt is the biological stain 'fast red B'
A 3-substituted propionyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any short-chain 3-substituted propionyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A 2,3-trans-enoyl CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any short-chain 2,3-trans-enoyl CoA (short-chain = chain length less than C6); major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxyether that is propan-1-ol substituted by an ethoxy group at position 3.
An octanoate ester obtained by the formal condensation of octanoic acid  with hexan-1-ol.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of (2R,3E)-5-oxopent-3-ene-1,2,5-tricarboxylic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A diazo compound in which the diazo group is attached to an  ethylidene group.
A fatty acid methyl ester of 10-undecenoic acid.
A fatty acid methyl ester of lauric acid.
The acetate ester of octan-1-ol.
A formate ester of  octan-1-ol.

A branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of a linear sequence of two alpha-sialyl residues, a beta-Dgalactosyl residue and an N-acetyl-D-glucosamine residue linked respectively (2->8), (2->8) and (1->4), to the galactosyl residue of which is also linked (1->4) an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue. It is the carbohydrate portion of ganglioside GD2 with undefined anomeric stereochemistry at the reducing-end galactose residue.
A member of the class of bromobenzenes that is bromobenzene substituted by a cyclopropyl group at position 4.
A primary alcohol that is undecane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1.
A benzoate ester obtained by the formal condensation of benzoic acid with isobutanol.
A fatty acid ethyl ester of nonanoic acid.
An alkylamine that is pent-3-en-1-amine substituted by a methyl group ay position 4.
A carboxylic ester obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 3-(methylthio)propionic acid with ethanol.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of 2-hydroxyhepta-2,4-diene-1,7-dioic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of tetrahydrothiophenes that is thiolane substituted by a methyl group at position 2 and an oxo group at position 3 respectively.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of (4Z)-2-oxohept-4-enedioic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A methyl ketone that is pent-1-ene substituted by an oxo group at position 4.
A tricarboxylic acid that is pent-3-ene-1,2,5-tricarboxylic acid carrying an oxo substituent at position 5 (the 2R,3E-stereoisomer).
The acetate ester of  hexan-1-ol.
The acetate ester of nonan-1-ol.
A carboxylic ester obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 3-hydroxy-3-phenylpropionic acid with ethanol.
A fatty acid ethyl ester of 2-hexenoic acid.
